data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  span  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each `nint` is 8 bytes. The elements are stack-allocated and accessible through the span as expected. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types (they're aliases for `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr` with arithmetic support).
